        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>British Museum</placeName>
                    <date>20 Sept. Friday. </date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I beg Your pardon of not being able to come yesterday, but You were treatened with a foreign invasion and to save You the bother of two separate visits I sacrificed the pleasure of having You all to myself and intended to join the invaders. However there is no more danger now and if You will allow me I’ll call at Down on Sunday by the 2<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>30 train returning at 9’ or, if the morning hours are more comfortable to You, I will come by a morning train and return in the afternoon.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Your very truly | W. Kowalevsky</p>
<p>P.S. To save You writing a letter I will take the liberty to consider Your silence as a sign of approval.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note>1.5 the 2<hi rend="superscript">o</hi> … 9’]‘3<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 9’— Here at <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> to 4’ <hi rend="italic">pencil</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to Kovalevsky’s visit to Down, which took place on 22 September 1872 (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Kovalevsky visited Down on 22 September 1872 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
